        <h2>Executive Summary</h2>
        <p>This report documents the findings of a manual penetration test against OWASP Juice Shop, a deliberately vulnerable web application used for security training. Five distinct vulnerabilities were identified and exploited, ranging from SQL injection to information exposure. The objective was to simulate real‑world attack techniques and provide actionable remediation advice. All findings have been reproduced and validated.</p>

        <h2>Scope & Methodology</h2>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Application:</strong> OWASP Juice Shop (Heroku deployment)</li>
            <li><strong>Approach:</strong> Black‑box manual testing</li>
            <li><strong>Techniques:</strong> SQLi, XSS, IDOR, forced browsing, error analysis</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Summary of Findings</h2>
        <table>
            <thead>
                <tr><th>ID</th><th>Vulnerability</th><th>Severity</th><th>Endpoint</th></tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
                <tr><td>TRACE-01</td><td>SQL Injection (Auth Bypass)</td><td><span class="badge badge-high">HIGH</span></td><td>Login form</td></tr>
                <tr><td>TRACE-02</td><td>Reflected / DOM XSS</td><td><span class="badge badge-medium">MEDIUM</span></td><td>Search bar</td></tr>
                <tr><td>TRACE-03</td><td>IDOR – Confidential Document</td><td><span class="badge badge-medium">MEDIUM</span></td><td>/ftp directory</td></tr>
                <tr><td>TRACE-04</td><td>Sensitive Information Exposure</td><td><span class="badge badge-low">LOW/MED</span></td><td>/metrics endpoint</td></tr>
                <tr><td>TRACE-05</td><td>Poor Error Handling</td><td><span class="badge badge-info">INFO</span></td><td>Login error trigger</td></tr>
            </tbody>
        </table>

        <!-- Vuln 1 EN -->
        <div class="vuln-block">
            <div class="vuln-title">
                <span>🔓 TRACE-01: SQL Injection – Authentication Bypass</span>
                <span class="badge badge-high">HIGH</span>
            </div>
            <div class="meta">Location: Login page (email parameter)</div>
            <p><strong>Description</strong><br>The login endpoint is vulnerable to union-based SQL injection. By injecting a crafted payload into the email field, an attacker can force the SQL query to return a valid password from the <code>admins</code> table, completely bypassing password verification.</p>
            <p><strong>Steps to reproduce</strong></p>
            <ol>
                <li>Go to login page <code>/#/login</code></li>
                <li>In the <strong>Email</strong> field, input:</li>
                <div class="code-block">' UNION SELECT 'pass' AS password FROM admins WHERE '1' = '1</div>
                <li>In the <strong>Password</strong> field, enter anything (e.g., "dummy")</li>
                <li>Click "Log in"</li>
            </ol>
            <p><strong>Result</strong><br>Successful authentication as administrator. The challenge "Privacy Policy" is marked as solved, and the attacker gains full access to the application.</p>
            <div class="screenshot-placeholder">
                📸 <strong>Evidence:</strong> <i>image1.png</i> – Main shop page after SQLi login, showing solved challenge and authenticated session.
            </div>
            <p><strong>Impact</strong><br>Complete account takeover, privilege escalation, and potential data breach.</p>
            <p><strong>Remediation</strong><br>Use parameterized queries (prepared statements) or an ORM. Never concatenate user input directly into SQL. Implement allow-list input validation.</p>
        </div>

        <!-- Vuln 2 EN -->
        <div class="vuln-block">
            <div class="vuln-title">
                <span>⚠️ TRACE-02: Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) – Reflected & DOM</span>
                <span class="badge badge-medium">MEDIUM</span>
            </div>
            <div class="meta">Location: Search bar</div>
            <p><strong>Description</strong><br>The search functionality does not sanitize user-supplied input, allowing injection of arbitrary HTML/JavaScript. Two payloads were tested: a classic <code>&lt;iframe&gt;</code> with <code>javascript:alert()</code> and a more complex SoundCloud embed that solved the "Bonus Payload" DOM XSS challenge.</p>
            <p><strong>Payload 1 (Reflected XSS)</strong></p>
            <div class="code-block">&lt;iframe src="javascript:alert('XSS')"&gt;</div>
            <p><strong>Payload 2 (DOM XSS / bonus)</strong></p>
            <div class="code-block">&lt;iframe width="100%" height="166" scrolling="no" frameborder="no" allow="autoplay" src="https://w.soundcloud.com/player/?url=https%3A//api.soundcloud.com/tracks/771984076&color=%23ff5000&auto_play=true&hide_related=false&show_comments=true&show_user=true&show_reposts=false&show_teaser=true&~&lt;/iframe&gt;</div>
            <p><strong>Result</strong><br>JavaScript alert is triggered, and the application solves the "Bonus Payload" challenge, confirming XSS exploitation.</p>
            <div class="screenshot-placeholder">
                📸 <strong>Evidence:</strong> <i>image2.png</i> (alert execution) and <i>image3.png</i> (bonus payload solved).
            </div>
            <p><strong>Impact</strong><br>Session hijacking, phishing, defacement, or arbitrary actions performed in the context of the victim user.</p>
            <p><strong>Remediation</strong><br>Apply context-aware output encoding (HTML entity encoding). Use Content Security Policy (CSP) to block inline script execution. Sanitize with libraries like DOMPurify.</p>
        </div>

        <!-- Vuln 3 EN -->
        <div class="vuln-block">
            <div class="vuln-title">
                <span>📁 TRACE-03: IDOR – Insecure Direct Object Reference</span>
                <span class="badge badge-medium">MEDIUM</span>
            </div>
            <div class="meta">Location: FTP directory traversal via About Us page</div>
            <p><strong>Description</strong><br>By manually changing the URL from the About Us page, an attacker can navigate to the server's <code>/ftp</code> directory and access a confidential business document without any authentication or authorization checks.</p>
            <p><strong>Steps to reproduce</strong></p>
            <ol>
                <li>Open the About Us page: <code>/#/about</code></li>
                <li>Modify the URL to <code>https://juice-shop.herokuapp.com/ftp</code></li>
                <li>Locate the file <code>acquisitions.md</code> (or similar)</li>
                <li>Open the file directly – content is disclosed</li>
            </ol>
            <p><strong>Result</strong><br>Full text of "Planned Acquisitions" is displayed, marked as confidential.</p>
            <div class="screenshot-placeholder">
                📸 <strong>Evidence:</strong> <i>image4.png</i> – Shows the acquisitions document with confidentiality notice.
            </div>
            <p><strong>Impact</strong><br>Leakage of internal strategic plans, which could be used for competitive or financial gain.</p>
            <p><strong>Remediation</strong><br>Implement proper access control on every endpoint and static resource. Store sensitive files outside the web root and use a secure download handler with permission checks.</p>
        </div>

        <!-- Vuln 4 EN -->
        <div class="vuln-block">
            <div class="vuln-title">
                <span>📊 TRACE-04: Sensitive Information Exposure (Metrics Endpoint)</span>
                <span class="badge badge-low">LOW/MED</span>
            </div>
            <div class="meta">Location: <code>/metrics</code></div>
            <p><strong>Description</strong><br>The application exposes a Prometheus metrics endpoint without any authentication. This endpoint reveals internal operational data that can assist an attacker in fingerprinting and planning further attacks.</p>
            <p><strong>Steps to reproduce</strong></p>
            <div class="code-block">curl https://juice-shop.herokuapp.com/metrics</div>
            <p><strong>Information disclosed includes:</strong></p>
            <ul>
                <li>HTTP request counts grouped by status (2XX, 4XX, 5XX)</li>
                <li>File upload success/error counters</li>
                <li>Application startup durations (db creation, FTP cleanup, etc.)</li>
                <li>Process CPU, memory, and start time</li>
            </ul>
            <div class="screenshot-placeholder">
                📸 <strong>Evidence:</strong> <i>image5.png</i> – Snippet of the metrics output in Prometheus format.
            </div>
            <p><strong>Impact</strong><br>Attackers can infer usage patterns, system resources, and internal component details, increasing the likelihood of a successful targeted attack.</p>
            <p><strong>Remediation</strong><br>Restrict access to <code>/metrics</code> to trusted internal networks using firewall rules or reverse proxy authentication. Enable basic auth or API key for monitoring endpoints in production.</p>
        </div>

        <!-- Vuln 5 EN -->
        <div class="vuln-block">
            <div class="vuln-title">
                <span>⚠️ TRACE-05: Poor Error Handling</span>
                <span class="badge badge-info">INFORMATIVE</span>
            </div>
            <div class="meta">Location: Login form (malformed input)</div>
            <p><strong>Description</strong><br>When the application receives unexpected input (e.g., malformed SQL in the email field), it fails to handle the error gracefully. Instead of a custom error page, the server returns a generic Heroku error iframe, revealing that an unhandled exception occurred.</p>
            <p><strong>Steps to reproduce</strong></p>
            <ol>
                <li>Go to login page</li>
                <li>In the Email field, enter:</li>
                <div class="code-block">UNION SELECT null—</div>
                <li>Enter any password and submit</li>
            </ol>
            <p><strong>Result</strong><br>The page shows an embedded Heroku error frame and the raw injected payload appears on screen. The challenge "Error Handling" is solved.</p>
            <div class="screenshot-placeholder">
                📸 <strong>Evidence:</strong> <i>image6.png</i> – Error page with payload visible and solved challenge.
            </div>
            <p><strong>Impact</strong><br>Information disclosure (database presence, platform details) and poor user experience. May aid attackers in refining injection attacks.</p>
            <p><strong>Remediation</strong><br>Implement a global exception handler that returns sanitized, user‑friendly messages. Log full errors server‑side only. Avoid exposing any system details to clients.</p>
        </div>

        <h2>Remediation Roadmap (Priority Order)</h2>
        <ol>
            <li><strong>Immediate (Critical):</strong> Fix SQL injection using parameterized queries – prevents authentication bypass and data leakage.</li>
            <li><strong>High:</strong> Implement access controls for <code>/ftp</code> and all static directories (IDOR protection).</li>
            <li><strong>Medium:</strong> Apply output encoding / CSP to eliminate XSS in search and other input vectors.</li>
            <li><strong>Low/Defense in depth:</strong> Protect <code>/metrics</code> with authentication or IP whitelist.</li>
            <li><strong>Informational:</strong> Replace generic error pages with custom safe error handlers.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2>Conclusion</h2>
        <p>The OWASP Juice Shop application, while designed as a training target, contains real vulnerabilities that are prevalent in many production systems. The identified issues – especially SQL injection and IDOR – pose serious risks if present in live environments. Applying the recommended countermeasures will drastically reduce the attack surface and align with secure coding best practices.</p>
        <p>This report is intended for educational use and GitHub portfolio demonstration. All tests were performed responsibly in an isolated training environment.</p>
    </div>

